ario: Epididymal cyst/spermatocele"},{"id":"3c3ad5fd-d565-5f54-87cc-f33c2fd5e99e","slug":"varicocele","fullItemName":"Scenario: Varicocele"},{"id":"42465c6c-cc4f-563f-b631-849c7330a5fb","slug":"hydrocele","fullItemName":"Scenario: Hydrocele"}]},{"id":"54eca506-beb4-5707-9686-73ad11c9500d","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"9b67969f-fc26-5cac-b61d-05a832131aad","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"c7a76cc1-2479-5219-948a-de6fd1df394c","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"5bb65ffb-d88a-57bd-afa4-34a94eadaeb1","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"bd50fb8b-903a-5e6d-a9ae-4e8f6ae9b3f8","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"33cc43a6-9f1d-5245-968d-5e59759b5cb9","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"81104ab4-a95d-5ecf-bdcc-24e0a1b8a3cd","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"2dc88556-8fc4-51f7-8e4e-0590678dd6fb","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"487587a8-13ea-5ad1-b569-493005013fa2","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"50fcd3eb-b8cd-549e-8d98-58b99fc93ea5","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field d9993bcb-c2f6-4840-a360-2ba5e5202389 --><h3>How should I manage a man or boy with suspected testicular torsion?</h3><!-- end field d9993bcb-c2f6-4840-a360-2ba5e5202389 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 18ec9f07-b380-450a-bfa2-eb38a5703763 --><!-- begin field b738606e-a0c4-47a6-98b3-db55e724c42f --><ul><li><strong>If testicular torsion is suspected, admit immediately </strong>to urology or paediatric surgery.</li><li>Acute testicular pain, often with abdominal pain and sometimes vomiting has a high predictive value for testicular torsion. The patient should be kept fasted and a surgical referral should be made without delay</li><li>If the man or boy has no current scrotal swelling, but gives a history of previous episodes of severe, self-limiting pain or swelling, refer for an outpatient appointment with a urologist, the urgency depending on the frequency and duration of episodes.<ul><li>Chronic intermittent torsion can result in segmental ischaemia of the testis. </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field b738606e-a0c4-47a6-98b3-db55e724c42f --><!-- end item 18ec9f07-b380-450a-bfa2-eb38a5703763 -->","subChapters":[{"id":"cb6140db-885f-5eac-b311-948afb9cdc73","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-9d4","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 4834a376-1e09-4c87-b4ae-950f1b51e3e0 --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 4834a376-1e09-4c87-b4ae-950f1b51e3e0 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 9d42c83d-925e-4462-96b2-ed047b39c706 --><!-- begin field d78f6022-0f6b-4913-927f-ab607a158b38 --><p>These recommendations are based on the British Medical Journal (BMJ) best practice guides, <em>Testicular torsion</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">BMJ, 2019</a>]  and a narrative review <em>Testicular torsion: diagnosis, evaluation and management</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Sharp et al, 2013</a>].</p><ul><li>Testicular torsion requires surgical detorsion as soon as possible (within 4–8 hours) before ischaemic damage occurs, which results in reduced fertility and even testicular loss [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Sharp et al, 2013</a>].</li><li>Rates of salvage of the affected testis decrease with time from the onset of symptoms, from 90% at 6 hours to less than 10% at 24 hours or more [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Sharp et al, 2013</a>].</li><li>A history of previous episodes of severe, self-limiting scrotal pain and swelling are assumed to be spontaneous torsion and detorsion [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Sharp et al, 2013</a>].</li><li>In patients with a history and physical examination suggestive of torsion, imaging studies should NOT be performed as they may delay treatment, therefore prolonging the ischaemic time. Negative surgical exploration is preferable to a missed diagnosis as all imaging studies have a false-negative rate.  </li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">East Midlands Clinical Networks, 2019</a>] </p><!-- end field d78f6022-0f6b-4913-927f-ab607a158b38 --><!-- end item 9d42c83d-925e-4462-96b2-ed047b39c706 -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}